  "raw_response": "{\n  \"title\": \"Bullish Demand Zones on EUR/USD 4H: Identifying Valid Long Entries Using Inefficiency, BOS, and Liquidity Sweep\",\n  \"school\": \"Smart Money Concepts (SMC)\",\n  \"asset\": \"EURUSD\",\n  \"timeframe\": \"4H\",\n  \"market_context\": \"Price in a clear bullish trend with higher highs and higher lows; recent break above a key supply zone signaled shift to bullish bias. Analyst focuses on identifying demand zones that satisfy the three criteria: inefficiency (imbalance), break of structure, and liquidity sweep.\",\n  \"key_observation\": \"The analyst identifies demand zones as the last bullish candle before an inefficiency (e.g., FVG or sharp move up), emphasizing that price returning to this zone may trigger rejection and offer a long entry.\",\n  \"analysis_steps\": [\n    \"Step 1: Confirm the market is in a bullish trend by observing higher highs and higher lows on the 4H chart.\",\n    \"Step 2: Identify the most recent key supply zone that was broken upward, confirming a shift in market direction.\",\n    \"Step 3: Locate potential demand zones using the three criteria: presence of inefficiency (e.g., FVG), prior break of structure, and a liquidity sweep (e.g., wick into prior swing low).\",\n    \"Step 4: Mark the demand zone as the last bullish candle before the inefficiency, since decisions are made during that candle before smart money enters.\",\n    \"Step 5: Evaluate whether price returns to the demand zone and shows rejection (e.g., bullish engulfing, pin bar) for a potential long entry.\"",
